Animating mobile web content javascript can easily produce clunky looking animation unless you follow these guideines.
<ol>
	<li><strong>Don't Manipulate the DOM while you're animating stuff.</strong> <br /> This will make animation clunky even on desktop browsers. DOM manipulation includes adding or removing elements from the DOM -or- changing attributes of DOM elements (including class names or other attributes). DOM manipulation can even occurr in ways you wouldn't expect -- say if you've got custom analytics event scripting. If you absolutely have to do this kind of evented analytics (it's hard to get away from on a corporate development level) then you can at least defer your tracking events. <a href="https://github.com/keeganbrown/ActionDeferr" title="This might help." target="_blank">This script I wrote might help</a>. </li>
<!--more-->
	<li><strong>Prevent scrolling.</strong> <br /> Scrolling the page on most mobile devices (including some tablets) will often prevent all animation from occurring until the scroll stops.</li>
	<li><strong>Leverage a little CSS3.</strong> CSS3 animations and transitions can go a long way to making Javascript animations perform like butter on mobile devices. Even if you're still animating with plain 'ol jQuery, the following CSS3 can still help. <br /> 
<code> 
#box-around-animated-content {
	-webkit-transform: translate3d(0,0,0);
	-moz-transform: translate3d(0,0,0);
	-ms-transform: translate3d(0,0,0);
	transform: translate3d(0,0,0);
}
</code> <br/> Note that you might need to be a little reserved in how you apply this trick. Doing so engages hardware acceleration on the device, which can have some pretty weird side effects on your page. Use it sparingly -- using this trick on <strong>too many</strong> boxes on the page will cause the device to stop hardware acceleration altogether, and your animations will go back to being clunky. This trick works great on iOS devices and newer android devices. Be sure to check your page in older android devices if you use this trick.</li>
</ol>
